<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Chapter 7 Questions</title>

	<section xml:id="sec-area-between-curves">
		<title>Area Between Curves</title>

		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-area-between-curves-1-v1" component="proteus">
			<title> Matching Question </title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Match the region on the left to the expression representing its area on the right. (one to many)
					<me/><!-- Vertical space hack. Is there a better way? -->
				</p>
				
				<sidebyside widths="36% 64%">
					<p><m>\color{RoyalBlue}\small\text{Region bounded by}\ ⤵︎ </m></p>
					<p><m>\color{BurntOrange}\small\text{Area of the Region}\ ⤵︎</m></p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>

			<cardsort>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>y = \sqrt{x},\ y = 2,\ y</m>-axis </premise>
					<response> <m>\displaystyle\int_{-2}^{2} (4 - y^2)\ dy</m></response>
				</match>

				<match><response> <m>\sfrac{8}{3}</m> </response></match>

				<match><response> <m>\sfrac{9}{2}</m> </response></match>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>x = y^2,\ x = 4</m> </premise>
					<response> <m>\sfrac{11}{3}</m> </response>
				</match>

				<match><response> <m>\displaystyle 2\int^{\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}}_{\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2}} (y-1-\sqrt{y})\ dy</m> </response></match>

				<match><response> <m>\displaystyle 2\int_{0}^{4} \sqrt{x}\ dx</m> </response></match>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>y = x + 1,\ y = x^2</m> </premise>
					<response> <m>\displaystyle\int_0^3 (3y-y^2)\ dy</m> </response>
				</match>

				<match><response> <m>\displaystyle\int_{0}^{4} (2 - \sqrt{x})\ dx</m> </response></match>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>x = 3y - y^2,\ x = 0</m> </premise>
					<response> <m>\displaystyle\int_{0}^{2} y^2\ dy</m> </response>
				</match>

				<match><response> <m>\displaystyle 2\int^{\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}}_{\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2}} (x+1-x^2)\ dx</m> </response></match>

				<match><response> <m>\sfrac{32}{3}</m> </response></match>

				<match><response> <m>\sfrac{5\sqrt{5}}{3}</m> </response></match>
			</cardsort>
		</exercise>

		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-area-between-curves-2-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Multiple-Choice</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The region between <m>y = x^2</m> and <m>y = 6 - x</m> is best integrated:
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p>With respect to <m>x</m> (bottom ➜ top)</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>With respect to <m>y</m> (left ➜ right)</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>With respect to <m>x</m> (left ➜ right)</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>With respect to <m>y</m> (bottom ➜ top)</p></statement>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-area-between-curves-3-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Multiple-Choice</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The region between <m>x = 2y</m> and <m>x = y^2-4y</m> is best integrated:
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice>
					<statement><p>With respect to <m>x</m> (bottom ➜ top)</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p>With respect to <m>y</m> (left ➜ right)</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>With respect to <m>x</m> (left ➜ right)</p></statement>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>With respect to <m>y</m> (bottom ➜ top)</p></statement>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

	</section>

	<section xml:id="sec-disk">
		<title>Disk Method</title>
		<!-- ============================================================ -->
		<!-- Questions for sec_disk: Volume by Cross-Sectional Area;      -->
		<!-- Disk and Washer Methods                                      -->
		<!-- ============================================================ -->

		<!-- Place after the introduction of Theorem 7.2.1 (Volume By Cross-Sectional Area) -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-1-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Cross-Sectional Volume Formula</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A solid is oriented along the <m>x</m>-axis from <m>x=a</m> to <m>x=b</m>, and its cross-sectional area at position <m>x</m> is <m>A(x)</m>. Which integral gives the volume of the solid?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p><m>\displaystyle\int_a^b A(x)\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The volume of a thin slice at position <m>x</m> is approximately <m>A(x)\,\Delta x</m> (area times thickness). Summing these slices and taking a limit gives the definite integral <m>\int_a^b A(x)\, dx</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\displaystyle\int_a^b A(x)^2\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							We do not square the cross-sectional area. Each slice has volume <m>A(x)\,\Delta x</m>, not <m>A(x)^2\,\Delta x</m>. Squaring the radius (not the area) appears in the Disk Method, which is a specific case.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\displaystyle\int_a^b \pi\, A(x)\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The factor of <m>\pi</m> is not needed in the general formula. It only appears when the cross section is a circle (as in the Disk Method), because the area of a circle of radius <m>R</m> is <m>\pi R^2</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\displaystyle\frac{d}{dx}\big[A(x)\big]</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The derivative of the area function does not give volume. Volume is found by <em>integrating</em> cross-sectional area over the length of the solid.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after Key Idea 7.2.4 (Disk Method) to test the formula -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-2-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Disk Method Radius Identification</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The curve <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m> is revolved about the <m>x</m>-axis from <m>x=0</m> to <m>x=4</m>. Using the Disk Method, what is the radius function <m>R(x)</m> and the resulting volume integral?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p><m>R(x)=\sqrt{x}</m>, so <m>\displaystyle V = \pi\int_0^4 x\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The radius of each disk is the distance from the <m>x</m>-axis to the curve, which is <m>R(x)=\sqrt{x}</m>. Squaring gives <m>R(x)^2 = x</m>, so the volume is <m>\pi\int_0^4 x\, dx</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>R(x)=x</m>, so <m>\displaystyle V = \pi\int_0^4 x^2\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The radius is the <m>y</m>-value of the curve at each <m>x</m>, which is <m>\sqrt{x}</m>, not <m>x</m>. The function <m>y=\sqrt{x}</m> tells us the distance from the axis of rotation to the curve.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>R(x)=\sqrt{x}</m>, so <m>\displaystyle V = \pi\int_0^4 \sqrt{x}\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The radius is correct, but remember the Disk Method formula uses <m>R(x)^2</m>, not <m>R(x)</m>. So we need <m>(\sqrt{x})^2 = x</m> inside the integral.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>R(x)=x^2</m>, so <m>\displaystyle V = \pi\int_0^4 x^4\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The curve is <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m>, not <m>y = x^2</m>. The radius equals the <m>y</m>-value of the curve being revolved.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after Example 7.2.2 (pyramid volume) to reinforce slicing non-circular solids -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-3-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Disk Method vs. Washer Method</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					A student is setting up a volume integral for a solid of revolution.
					Which condition determines whether the <em>disk method</em> should be
					used instead of the <em>washer method</em>?
				</p>
			</statement>

			<choices randomize="yes">

				<!-- ═══ CORRECT ═══ -->
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							When one boundary of the region being rotated lies <em>on</em> the axis
							of rotation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! When one edge of the region coincides with the axis of
							rotation, the inner radius is zero, the cross-sectional "washer"
							collapses to a solid disk, and the volume formula simplifies to
							<m>V = \pi \int_a^b [f(x)]^2 \, dx</m>.  As soon as a gap opens
							between the region and the axis, both an outer radius <m>R</m> and
							an inner radius <m>r</m> are present and the washer formula
							<m>V = \pi \int_a^b \bigl([R(x)]^2 - [r(x)]^2\bigr) dx</m> is
							required.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							When the region is rotated about a <em>horizontal</em> axis.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Not quite. Both the disk method and the washer method work for
							rotation about <em>either</em> a horizontal or a vertical axis.
							The orientation of the axis determines whether you integrate with
							respect to <m>x</m> or <m>y</m>, but it does not determine which
							method to use.  The deciding factor is whether a gap exists between
							the region and the axis.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							When the region is bounded by a <em>single</em> function.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							This is a common mix-up.  In both methods the region is typically
							bounded by two curves (or a curve and a boundary line).  What
							distinguishes the methods is not the <em>number</em> of bounding
							functions, but whether one of those boundaries is the axis of
							rotation itself.  If it is, the inner radius vanishes and you use
							the disk method; if neither boundary coincides with the axis, you
							need the washer method.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							When the boundaries of the region are given by <em>functions of <m>x</m></em>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The method does not depend on whether the boundaries are functions of
							<m>x</m> or <m>y</m>.  Both methods can be applied in either case; the key is whether one of those boundaries coincides with the axis of rotation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							When the boundaries of a region intersect at <em>one</em> point.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The number of intersection points does not determine which method to use.  Even if the boundaries intersect at only one point, they may still both lie above the axis of rotation, creating a gap that requires the washer method.  Conversely, if they intersect at one point but one boundary coincides with the axis, the disk method applies.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>

			</choices>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after the Washer Method (Key Idea 7.2.10) is introduced -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-4-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Washer Method Matching (version 1)</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the region bounded by <m>y = x^2</m> and <m>y = 1</m> for <m>0 \le x \le 1</m>.
				</p>
				<sidebyside width="50%">
					<image>
						<latex-image>
							<xi:include href="tikz-figs/tikz-washer-x.tex" parse="text" />
						</latex-image>
					</image>
				</sidebyside>
				<p>
					Match each inner and outer radius pair with the axis of rotation that they correspond to in the Washer Method.
				</p>
				<sidebyside>
					<p><m>\small\text{Inner/Outer Radii}</m> ⤵︎</p>
					<p><m>\small\text{Axis of Rotation}</m> ⤵︎</p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					In the Washer Method, the cross section is an annular ring (washer). The volume of each washer is <m>\pi\big(R(x)^2 - r(x)^2\big)\,\Delta x</m>, where <m>R(x)</m> is the outside radius and <m>r(x)</m> is the inside radius.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(x) = x^2,\quad R(x) = 1</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = 0</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(y) = 0,\quad R(y) = \sqrt{y}</m></premise>
					<response><m>x = 0</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(x) = x^2 + 1,\quad R(x) = 2</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = -1</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(y) = 1,\quad R(y) = 1 + \sqrt{y}</m></premise>
					<response><m>x = -1</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(x) = 0,\quad R(x) = 1 - x^2</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = 1</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(y) = 1 - \sqrt{y},\quad R(y) = 1</m></premise>
					<response><m>x = 1</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(x) = 1,\quad R(x) = 2 - x^2</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = 2</m></response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after the Washer Method (Key Idea 7.2.10) is introduced -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-4-v2" component="proteus">
			<title>Washer Method Matching (version 2)</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the region bounded by <m>y = x^2</m> and <m>y = 1</m> for <m>0 \le x \le 1</m>.
				</p>
				<sidebyside width="50%">
					<image>
						<latex-image>
							<xi:include href="tikz-figs/tikz-washer-x.tex" parse="text" />
						</latex-image>
					</image>
				</sidebyside>
				<p>
					Match each inner and outer radius pair with the axis of rotation that they correspond to in the Washer Method.
				</p>
				<sidebyside widths="32% 68%">
					<p><m>\small\text{Inner/Outer Radii}</m> ⤵︎</p>
					<p><m>\small\text{Axis of Rotation}</m> ⤵︎</p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					In the Washer Method, the cross section is an annular ring (washer). The volume of each washer is <m>\pi\big(R(x)^2 - r(x)^2\big)\,\Delta x</m>, where <m>R(x)</m> is the outside radius and <m>r(x)</m> is the inside radius.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(x) = x^2</m></premise>
					<premise><m>R(x) = 1</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = 0</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(y) = 0</m></premise>
					<premise><m>R(y) = \sqrt{y}</m></premise>
					<response><m>x = 0</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(y) = 1 - \sqrt{y}</m></premise>
					<premise><m>R(y) = 1</m></premise>
					<response><m>x = 1</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
						<premise><m>r(x) = 1</m></premise>
						<premise><m>R(x) = 2 - x^2</m></premise>
						<response><m>y = 2</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(y) = 1</m></premise>
					<premise><m>r(x) = 0</m></premise>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</exercise>

		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-5-v1" language="math">
			<title>Construct the Volume Integral</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose the region bounded by 
					<me>y = x\ \text{and}\ y = x^2\ \text{for}\ 0 \le x \le 1</me>
					is revolved about the <m>x</m>-axis. 
				</p>
				<p>	
					Using the blocks below, construct integral that gives the volume using the washer method?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<blocks layout="horizontal" randomize="yes">
				<block order="1"><m>V = \pi</m></block>
				<block order="2"><m>\int_0^1\big(</m></block>
				<block order="3"><m>x^2</m></block>
				<block order="4"><m>-</m></block>
				<block order="5"><m>x^4</m></block>
				<block order="6"><m>\big)\ dx</m></block>
				<block correct="no"><m>V = 2\pi</m></block>
				<block correct="no"><m>+</m></block>
				<block correct="no"><m>\int_{-1}^{1}\big(</m></block>
				<block correct="no"><m>x</m></block>
			</blocks>
		</exercise>

		<!-- "Identify the Error" MCQ
				Skill tested: correctly applying an axis-of-rotation shift.
				A student forgets that radii are measured from y = -1, not y = 0.
				Place after axis-shift examples are introduced. -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-6-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Washer Method: Identify the Error</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The region bounded by <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m> and <m>y = x</m>
					for <m>0 \le x \le 1</m> is revolved about the line
					<m>y = -1</m>.
					A student sets up the following volume integral using the
					washer method:
					<me>V = \pi\int_0^1\Bigl[(\sqrt{x})^2 - x^2\Bigr]\,dx
							= \pi\int_0^1\bigl(x - x^2\bigr)\,dx.</me>
					Which statement best identifies the error in the student's work?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The radii were measured from <m>y = 0</m> instead of
							from the axis <m>y = -1</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct!  Because the axis <m>y=-1</m> lies
							<em>below</em> the region, each radius must be
							increased by <m>1</m> to account for the gap between
							the axis and the nearest boundary.  In general, when
							the axis is <m>y = c</m>, the radii are
							<m>R(x) = f(x) - c</m> and <m>r(x) = g(x) - c</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The limits of integration should run from <m>-1</m>
							to <m>1</m> to reflect the position of the axis.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  The limits of integration are determined by
							the <em>x</em>-extent of the region being rotated,
							which is still <m>[0,1]</m>.  Shifting the axis of
							rotation never changes the limits; it changes the
							radius expressions instead.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The outer and inner radii are swapped; it should be
							<m>R(x) = x</m> and <m>r(x) = \sqrt{x}</m> since
							<m>y = x \ge y = \sqrt{x}</m> on <m>[0,1]</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  On <m>[0,1]</m> we have
							<m>\sqrt{x} \ge x</m> (check: at <m>x = \tfrac{1}{4}</m>,
							<m>\sqrt{x} = \tfrac{1}{2} > \tfrac{1}{4} = x</m>),
							so <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m> is indeed the outer boundary.
							The student has the orientation right but is measuring
							radii from the wrong baseline.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The formula should use <m>2\pi</m> instead of
							<m>\pi</m> because the solid is generated by a full
							<m>360°</m> rotation.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  The washer-method formula is
							<m>V = \pi\int(R^2-r^2)\,dx</m>; the factor of
							<m>\pi</m> (not <m>2\pi</m>) already accounts for a
							full revolution.  The factor <m>2\pi</m> appears in
							the <em>shell</em> method, where it represents the
							circumference of a cylindrical shell.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>


		<!-- "Work Backwards" MCQ
				Skill tested: reading R and r at a specific x-value and deducing
				the axis of rotation. Reverses the usual direction of reasoning.
				Place after several axis-shift examples. -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-7-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Washer Method: Deduce the Axis of Rotation</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the region bounded by <m>y = 2x+1</m> and
					<m>y = x+1</m> for <m>0 \le x \le 2</m>.  This region is
					revolved about a horizontal axis <m>y = c</m> using the
					washer method.
				</p>
				<p>
					At <m>x = 1</m>, the resulting washer has outer radius
					<m>R = 4</m> and inner radius <m>r = 3</m>.
					What is the axis of rotation?
				</p>
				<p><m>y=</m> <fillin mode="number" answer="-1"/></p>	
			</statement>

			<evaluation>
				<evaluate>
					<test>
						<numcmp use-answer="yes"/>
					</test>
				</evaluate>
			</evaluation>

		</exercise>


		<!-- "Select All Correct" multi-select
				Skill tested: recognizing equivalent volume expressions for the
				same solid — the washer integral in x and the shell integral in y
				both produce the same number.
				Place after both washer and shell methods have been introduced. -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-disk-8-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Washer Method: Select All Correct Volume Integrals</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The region bounded by <m>y = x^2</m> and <m>y = 1</m> for
					<m>0 \le x \le 1</m> is revolved about the <m>x</m>-axis.
					<em>Select every integral below that correctly computes
					the volume of the resulting solid.</em>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>V = \pi\displaystyle\int_0^1\bigl(1 - x^4\bigr)\,dx</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct.  Using the washer method with vertical slices:
							the outer radius is <m>R(x) = 1</m> and the inner
							radius is <m>r(x) = x^2</m>, so
							<m>R^2 - r^2 = 1 - x^4</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>V = 2\pi\displaystyle\int_0^1 y\sqrt{y}\,dy</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct.  Using the shell method with horizontal
							shells (integrating in <m>y</m>): the shell at height
							<m>y</m> has radius <m>y</m> (distance to the
							<m>x</m>-axis) and length <m>\sqrt{y}</m>
							(from <m>x=0</m> to <m>x=\sqrt{y}</m>), giving
							<m>2\pi\int_0^1 y^{3/2}\,dy = \tfrac{4\pi}{5}</m>,
							which equals the washer-method result.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>V = \pi\displaystyle\int_0^1\bigl(1-x^2\bigr)^2\,dx</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  This computes <m>\pi\int(R - r)^2\,dx</m>,
							which is <em>not</em> the washer formula.  The correct
							integrand is <m>R^2 - r^2</m>, not
							<m>(R - r)^2</m>.  These are equal only when one
							radius is zero.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>V = \pi\displaystyle\int_0^1 x^4\,dx</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  This integral gives the volume of the
							inner solid alone (the region below <m>y = x^2</m>
							only).  The volume of the full washer-shaped solid
							requires subtracting the inner volume from the outer,
							i.e., <m>\pi\int_0^1(1 - x^4)\,dx</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>V = 2\pi\displaystyle\int_0^1\sqrt{y}\,dy</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  This is missing the radius factor
							<m>y</m> inside the integral.  In the shell method,
							both the radius <em>and</em> the height of each shell
							must appear: the integrand should be
							<m>y \cdot \sqrt{y} = y^{3/2}</m>, not
							just <m>\sqrt{y}</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

	</section>

	<section xml:id="sec-shell-method">
		<title>Shell Method</title>
		<!-- ============================================================ -->
		<!-- Shell Method Reading Checkpoint Questions                     -->
		<!-- Placement: throughout the narrative of sec_shell_method.ptx   -->
		<!-- ============================================================ -->

		<!-- Place after the shell volume derivation (lines 291–325)  -->
		<!-- where V ≈ 2π r h Δx is established from unrolling the shell. -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-1-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Unrolling a Cylindrical Shell</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A single cylindrical shell has radius <m>r</m>, height <m>h</m>, and thickness <m>\Delta x</m>. When the shell is <q>cut and unrolled,</q> the resulting shape is approximately a rectangular solid. What is the approximate volume of that rectangular solid?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p><m>2\pi r h\,\Delta x</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Correct — cutting the shell and laying it flat gives a rectangle with length <m>2\pi r</m> (the circumference), height <m>h</m>, and depth <m>\Delta x</m>, so <m>V \approx 2\pi r h\,\Delta x</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\pi r^2 h</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>This is the volume of a solid cylinder, not a thin cylindrical shell. The shell has a small thickness <m>\Delta x</m>, which must appear in the volume expression.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\pi r h\,\Delta x</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Close, but the circumference of the shell is <m>2\pi r</m>, not <m>\pi r</m>. When you unroll the shell, the length of the resulting rectangle is the full circumference.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>2\pi r^2\,\Delta x</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>This expression is missing the height <m>h</m>. The unrolled shell is a rectangular solid whose dimensions are <m>2\pi r</m> (length), <m>h</m> (height), and <m>\Delta x</m> (depth).</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place right after the Shell Method formula (Key Idea,     -->
		<!-- lines 428–441) and the two special cases (lines 443–462).     -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-2-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Shell Method Formula Components</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Match each component in the Shell Method formula, <m>V = 2\pi\displaystyle\int_a^b r(x)\,h(x)\, dx</m>, with its geometric meaning.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					In the Shell Method, <m>r(x)</m> is always the distance from the sample shell to the axis of rotation, and <m>h(x)</m> is the height of the shell (determined by the bounding curves). The factor <m>2\pi</m> comes from unrolling the shell into a rectangle of length <m>2\pi r</m>.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>r(x)</m></premise>
					<response>Distance from the axis of rotation to the shell</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>h(x)</m></premise>
					<response>Height of the cylindrical shell</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>2\pi</m></premise>
					<response>Comes from the circumference of the shell</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>dx</m></premise>
					<response>Thickness of the cylindrical shell</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\pi</m></premise>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after the special-case list (lines 443–462) where  -->
		<!-- r(x) = x when revolving around the y-axis is stated.         -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-3-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Radius When Revolving Around the <m>y</m>-axis</title>
			<statement correct="yes">
				<p>
					When using the Shell Method to revolve a region around the <m>y</m>-axis, the radius function is simply <m>r(x) = x</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					True — the radius of each shell is the horizontal distance from the shell to the axis of rotation. Since the <m>y</m>-axis is <m>x = 0</m>, the distance from <m>x</m> to <m>x = 0</m> is just <m>x</m>.
				</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after Example 7.3.1 (ex_shell1, lines 468–559)    -->
		<!-- which sets up and evaluates a shell integral around the       -->
		<!-- y-axis for y = 1/(1+x^2).                                    -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-4-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Setting Up a Shell Integral</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The region bounded by <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m>, <m>y = 0</m>, <m>x = 0</m>, and <m>x = 4</m> is revolved about the <m>y</m>-axis. Using the Shell Method, which integral gives the volume of the resulting solid?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p><m>\displaystyle 2\pi\int_0^4 x\sqrt{x}\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Correct — rotating about the <m>y</m>-axis means <m>r(x) = x</m>. The shell height is the vertical distance from <m>y = 0</m> to <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m>, so <m>h(x) = \sqrt{x}</m>. Therefore <m>V = 2\pi\int_0^4 x\cdot\sqrt{x}\, dx</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\displaystyle 2\pi\int_0^4 \sqrt{x}\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>This is missing the radius factor <m>r(x) = x</m>. The Shell Method integrand is <m>r(x)\cdot h(x)</m>, not just <m>h(x)</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\displaystyle \pi\int_0^4 \left(\sqrt{x}\right)^2\, dx</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>This is the Disk Method integral (cross-sectional area <m>\pi R^2</m>), not the Shell Method. The Shell Method uses <m>2\pi\int r(x)\,h(x)\, dx</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\displaystyle 2\pi\int_0^2 y\cdot y^2\, dy</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Switching to <m>y</m> would be appropriate for the Shell Method only if the axis of rotation were horizontal. Here the axis is the <m>y</m>-axis (vertical), so we integrate with respect to <m>x</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after the paragraph (lines 854–858) that introduces -->
		<!-- revolving around a horizontal axis and switching to y.         -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-5-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Horizontal Axis of Rotation</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					When using the Shell Method to revolve a region around a <em>horizontal</em> axis (such as the <m>x</m>-axis), the radius and height functions must be written in terms of:
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p><m>y</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Correct — when revolving around a horizontal axis with the Shell Method, the shells are horizontal. Their radius and height are measured as functions of <m>y</m>, and the integral is <m>2\pi\int r(y)\,h(y)\, dy</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>x</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>When the axis of rotation is horizontal, the shells stack vertically, so the natural variable is <m>y</m>, not <m>x</m>. (Using <m>x</m> would correspond to the Washer Method for a horizontal axis.)</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>Either <m>x</m> or <m>y</m>; it does not matter.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>The variable must match the orientation of the shells. For a horizontal axis, shells are horizontal, so <m>y</m> is the correct variable.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>A parameter <m>t</m>.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>A parameter is not needed here. The Shell Method uses either <m>x</m> or <m>y</m> depending on the axis orientation.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after Example 7.3.4 (ex_shell4, lines 1157–1437)  -->
		<!-- which highlights when the Shell Method is easier than the     -->
		<!-- Washer Method (sin(x) about the y-axis).                     -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-6-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Shell Method as an Alternative</title>
			<statement correct="no">
				<p>
					The Shell Method can only be used when the Washer Method fails.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					False — both methods can often be applied to the same problem. The Shell Method is an <em>alternative</em> to the Washer Method, not a last resort. Sometimes one method leads to a simpler integral than the other, so having both as options is valuable.
				</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after the Washer/Shell summary table (Key Idea,    -->
		<!-- lines 1443–1479) that compares the two methods.               -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-7-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Washer vs. Shell Method</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Match each integral form on the left with the method and axis of rotation on the right.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					The Washer Method always squares the radius functions (<m>R^2 - r^2</m>) and uses <m>\pi</m>, while the Shell Method multiplies the radius by the height and uses <m>2\pi</m>. The variable of integration tells you whether the method slices perpendicular or parallel to the axis.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\displaystyle 2\pi\int_a^b r(x)\,h(x)\, dx</m></premise>
					<response>Shell Method — vertical axis</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\displaystyle \pi\int_a^b \Big(R(x)^2 - r(x)^2\Big)\, dx</m></premise>
					<response>Washer Method — horizontal axis</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\displaystyle 2\pi\int_c^d r(y)\,h(y)\, dy</m></premise>
					<response>Shell Method — horizontal axis</response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\displaystyle \pi\int_c^d \Big(R(y)^2 - r(y)^2\Big)\, dy</m></premise>
					<response>Washer Method — vertical axis</response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after the Shell Method (Key Idea 7.3.x) is introduced -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-8-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Shell Method Matching (version 1)</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the region bounded by <m>y = x^2</m> and <m>y = 1</m>
					for <m>0 \le x \le 1</m>.
				</p>
				<sidebyside width="50%">
					<image>
						<latex-image>
							<xi:include href="tikz-figs/tikz-shell-x.tex" parse="text" />
						</latex-image>
					</image>
				</sidebyside>
				<p>
					Match each axis of rotation with the radius–height pair 
					it corresponds to in the Shell Method.
				</p>
				<sidebyside widths="32% 68%">
					<p><m>\small\text{Axis of Rotation}</m> ⤵︎</p>
					<p><m>\small\text{Radius / Height}</m> ⤵︎</p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					In the Shell Method, each cylindrical shell has volume
					<m>2\pi\,(\text{radius})(\text{height})\,\Delta x</m>
					(or <m>\Delta y</m>). The <em>radius</em> is the
					perpendicular distance from the shell to the axis of rotation,
					and the <em>height</em> is the length of the shell parallel
					to the axis.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>x = 0</m></premise>
					<response><m>\text{radius} = x,\quad \text{height} = 1 - x^2</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>y = 0</m></premise>
					<response><m>\text{radius} = y,\quad \text{height} = \sqrt{y}</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>x = 1</m></premise>
					<response><m>\text{radius} = 1 - x,\quad \text{height} = 1 - x^2</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>y = 1</m></premise>
					<response><m>\text{radius} = 1 - y,\quad \text{height} = \sqrt{y}</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>x = -1</m></premise>
					<response><m>\text{radius} = x + 1,\quad \text{height} = 1 - x^2</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>y = -1</m></premise>
					<response><m>\text{radius} = y + 1,\quad \text{height} = \sqrt{y}</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>y = 2</m></premise>
					<response><m>\text{radius} = 2 - y,\quad \text{height} = \sqrt{y}</m></response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</exercise>

		<!-- Place after the Shell Method (Key Idea 7.3.x) is introduced -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-9-v2" component="proteus">
			<title>Shell Method Matching (version 2)</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the region bounded by <m>y = x^2</m> and <m>y = 1</m>
					for <m>0 \le x \le 1</m>.
				</p>
				<sidebyside width="50%">
					<image>
						<latex-image>
							<xi:include href="tikz-figs/tikz-washer-x.tex" parse="text" />
						</latex-image>
					</image>
				</sidebyside>
				<p>
					Match each radius–height pair with the axis of rotation
					it corresponds to in the Shell Method.
				</p>
				<sidebyside widths="32% 68%">
					<p><m>\small\text{Radius / Height}</m> ⤵︎</p>
					<p><m>\small\text{Axis of Rotation}</m> ⤵︎</p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					In the Shell Method, each cylindrical shell has volume
					<m>2\pi\,(\text{radius})(\text{height})\,\Delta x</m>
					(or <m>\Delta y</m>). The <em>radius</em> is the
					perpendicular distance from the shell to the axis of rotation,
					and the <em>height</em> is the length of the shell parallel
					to the axis.
				</p>
			</feedback>
			<cardsort>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\text{radius} = x</m></premise>
					<premise><m>\text{height} = 1 - x^2</m></premise>
					<response><m>x = 0</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\text{radius} = y</m></premise>
					<premise><m>\text{height} = \sqrt{y}</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = 0</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\text{radius} = 1 - x</m></premise>
					<premise><m>\text{height} = 1 - x^2</m></premise>
					<response><m>x = 1</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\text{radius} = 1 - y</m></premise>
					<premise><m>\text{height} = \sqrt{y}</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = 1</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\text{radius} = 2 - y</m></premise>
					<premise><m>\text{height} = \sqrt{y}</m></premise>
					<response><m>y = 2</m></response>
				</match>
				<match>
					<premise><m>\text{radius} = 1 - x^2</m></premise>
					<premise><m>\text{height} = x</m></premise>
				</match>
			</cardsort>
		</exercise>

		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-10-v1" language="math">
			<title>Construct the Volume Integral (Shell Method)</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose the region bounded by
					<me>y = x\ \text{and}\ y = x^2\ \text{for}\ 0 \le x \le 1</me>
					is revolved about the <m>y</m>-axis.
				</p>
				<p>
					Using the blocks below, construct the integral that gives the
					volume using the shell method.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<blocks layout="horizontal" randomize="yes">
				<block order="1"><m>V = 2\pi</m></block>
				<block order="2"><m>\int_0^1</m></block>
				<block order="3"><m>x\ (</m></block>
				<block order="4"><m>x</m></block>
				<block order="5"><m>-</m></block>
				<block order="6"><m>x^2</m></block>
				<block order="7"><m>)\ dx</m></block>
				<block correct="no"><m>V = \pi</m></block>
				<block correct="no"><m>\int_{-1}^{1}</m></block>
				<block correct="no"><m>x^4</m></block>
			</blocks>
		</exercise>

		<!-- "Identify the Error" MCQ
				Skill tested: correctly computing the radius when the axis of
				rotation is a vertical line other than x = 0.
				Place after off-axis shell examples are introduced. -->
		<exercise label="APEX-PROTEUS-shell-11-v1" component="proteus">
			<title>Shell Method: Identify the Error</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The region bounded by <m>y = x^2</m> and <m>y = 0</m> for
					<m>0 \le x \le 2</m> is revolved about the line
					<m>x = 3</m>.  A student sets up the following integral:
					<me>V = 2\pi\int_0^2 x \cdot x^2\,dx = 2\pi\int_0^2 x^3\,dx.</me>
					Which statement best identifies the error?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							The radius of each shell is the distance from the
							shell to the axis <m>x = 3</m>, which is
							<m>3 - x</m>, not <m>x</m>.  The correct integral is
							<m>V = 2\pi\displaystyle\int_0^2
							(3-x)\cdot x^2\,dx</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct!  When revolving about <m>x = c</m> with
							<m>c &gt; b</m>, the shell at position <m>x</m> has
							radius <m>c - x</m> (the horizontal distance to the
							axis).  Using <m>x</m> alone assumes the axis is the
							<m>y</m>-axis (<m>x = 0</m>), which is not the case
							here.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The limits of integration should run from <m>0</m>
							to <m>3</m> to match the position of the axis.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  The limits of integration always span
							the <m>x</m>-extent of the region being revolved,
							which is <m>[0,2]</m>.  Moving the axis of rotation
							does not change the limits; it changes the
							<em>radius expression</em> inside the integrand.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The height of each shell should be <m>2 - x^2</m>
							rather than <m>x^2</m>, because the height is
							measured downward from <m>y = 2</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  The height of a shell is the vertical
							extent of the region at a given <m>x</m>, which is
							<m>x^2 - 0 = x^2</m>.  The value <m>y = 2</m> has
							no special role in this problem; the upper boundary
							is the parabola <m>y = x^2</m>, not a horizontal
							line.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The factor <m>2\pi</m> should be replaced by
							<m>\pi</m>, because the axis of rotation is a
							vertical line rather than a horizontal one.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect.  The factor <m>2\pi</m> in the shell
							method represents the circumference of each
							cylindrical shell and is always present regardless
							of whether the axis is horizontal or vertical.  The
							orientation of the axis determines the variable of
							integration and the radius expression, not the
							leading constant.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>

	</section>

</chapter>